---
const features = [
  {
    title: "Real-time multiplayer",
    body: "Race against others with low-latency networking — the core distributed-systems piece of the project.",
  },
  {
    title: "Spectator mode",
    body: "Drop in to watch live matches with full camera controls and a results table.",
  },
  {
    title: "Built in pygame-ce",
    body: "A modern fork of pygame with better performance and SDL2 under the hood.",
  },
];
---

<section id="about" class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">
  <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-[1fr_1.2fr] gap-12 items-start">
    <div>
      <h2
        class="font-[family-name:var(--font-display)] text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight"
      >
        About the game
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[color:var(--color-muted)] leading-relaxed">
        Skyward Race started as the final project for CS323 — Parallel and
        Distributed Computing. It's a small competitive racer that uses
        client–server networking, with rooms, spectators, and a results
        screen. The pygame-ce build is the one you can download today.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[color:var(--color-muted)] leading-relaxed">
        It's now being ported to Godot 4.6 to grow beyond the original scope —
        track that journey in the
        <a href="#devlog" class="text-[color:var(--color-accent)] hover:underline"
          >Godot port section</a
        >.
      </p>
    </div>

    <ul class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      {
        features.map((f) => (
          <li class="bg-[color:var(--color-bg-elev)] border border-white/5 rounded-xl p-5">
            <h3 class="font-[family-name:var(--font-display)] font-semibold text-lg">
              {f.title}
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[color:var(--color-muted)] leading-relaxed">
              {f.body}
            </p>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>
